WEBVTT

00:21.620 --> 00:24.420
CHAPTER II.

00:24.420 --> 00:26.460
Matthew Cuthbert is surprised.

00:28.140 --> 00:33.060
Matthew Cuthbert and the sorrel mare jogged comfortably over the eight miles to Bright River.

00:33.640 --> 00:44.520
It was a pretty road, running along between snug farmsteads, with now and again a bit of balsam-y fir wood to drive through, or a hollow where wild plums hung out their filmy bloom.

00:45.360 --> 00:52.580
The air was sweet with the breath of many apple orchards, and the meadows sloped away in the distance to horizon mists of pearl and purple,

00:52.580 --> 00:58.380
while the little birds sang as if it were the one day of summer in all the year.

00:59.300 --> 01:06.020
Matthew enjoyed the drive after his own fashion, except during the moments when he met women and had to nod to them,

01:06.400 --> 01:12.560
for in Prince Edward Island you are supposed to nod to all and sundry you meet on the road whether you know them or not.

01:13.420 --> 01:16.600
Matthew dreaded all women except Marilla and Mrs. Rachel.

01:17.020 --> 01:21.420
He had an uncomfortable feeling that the mysterious creatures were secretly laughing at him.

01:21.420 --> 01:35.000
He may have been quite right in thinking so, for he was an odd-looking personage, with an ungainly figure and long iron-grey hair that touched his stooping shoulders and a full soft brown beard that he had worn ever since he was twenty.

01:35.600 --> 01:41.100
In fact, he looked at twenty very much as he looked at sixty, lacking a little of the grayness.

01:42.100 --> 01:45.260
When he reached Bright River there was no sign of any train.

01:45.260 --> 01:52.240
He thought he was too early, so he tied his horse in the yard of the small Bright River Hotel and went over to the station.

01:53.280 --> 02:00.900
The long platform was almost deserted, the only living creature in sight being a girl who was sitting on a pile of shingles at the extreme end.

02:01.780 --> 02:07.100
Matthew, barely noting that it was a girl, sidled past her as quickly as possible without looking at her.

02:07.620 --> 02:13.340
Had he looked, he could hardly have failed to notice the tense rigidity and expectation of her attitude and expression.

02:14.090 --> 02:22.880
She was sitting there waiting for something or somebody, and since sitting and waiting was the only thing to do just then, she sat and waited with all her might in mind.

02:24.340 --> 02:32.940
Matthew encountered the stationmaster locking up the ticket office preparatory to going home for supper, and asked him if the five-thirty train would soon be along.

02:33.720 --> 02:42.840
The five-thirty train has been in and gone half an hour ago, answered that brisk official, but there was a passenger dropped off for you, a little girl.

02:43.100 --> 02:44.660
She's sitting out there on the shingles.

02:45.180 --> 02:50.700
I asked her to go into the lady's waiting room, but she informed me gravely that she preferred to stay outside.

02:51.580 --> 02:54.000
There was more scope for imagination, she said.

02:54.660 --> 02:56.440
She's a case, I should say.

02:57.140 --> 03:00.480
I'm not expecting a girl, said Matthew blankly.

03:00.920 --> 03:02.340
It's a boy I've come for.

03:02.760 --> 03:08.200
He should be here. Mrs. Alexander Spencer was to bring him over from Nova Scotia for me.

03:09.120 --> 03:10.700
The stationmaster whistled.

03:11.540 --> 03:13.460
Guess there's some mistake, he said.

03:14.020 --> 03:17.820
Mrs. Spencer came off the train with that girl and gave her into my charge.

03:18.340 --> 03:23.440
Said you and your sister were adopting her from an orphan asylum, and that you would be along for her presently.

03:23.680 --> 03:25.320
That's all I know about it.

03:25.320 --> 03:28.180
And I haven't got any more orphans concealed hereabouts.

03:29.500 --> 03:35.340
I don't understand, said Matthew helplessly, wishing that Marilla was at hand to cope with the situation.

03:36.420 --> 03:39.800
Well, you'd better question the girl, said the stationmaster carelessly.

03:40.160 --> 03:44.640
I dare say she'll be able to explain. She's got a tongue of her own, that's certain.

03:45.320 --> 03:47.560
Maybe they were out of boys of the brand you wanted.

03:48.260 --> 03:56.520
He walked jauntily away being hungry, and the unfortunate Matthew was left to do that which was harder for him than bearding a lion in its den,

03:57.140 --> 04:03.360
walk up to a girl, a strange girl, an orphan girl, and demand of her why she wasn't a boy.

04:04.540 --> 04:09.340
Matthew groaned in spirit as he turned about and shuffled gently down the platform towards her.

04:10.180 --> 04:14.500
She had been watching him ever since he had passed her, and she had her eyes on him now.

04:14.500 --> 04:19.480
Matthew was not looking at her and would not have seen what she was really like if he had been.

04:20.020 --> 04:22.960
But an ordinary observer would have seen this.

04:23.700 --> 04:29.960
A child of about eleven, garbed in a very short, very tight, very ugly dress of yellowish-grey wincey,

04:30.560 --> 04:38.400
she wore a faded brown sailor hat, and beneath the hat, extending down her back, were two braids of very thick, decidedly red hair.

04:39.040 --> 04:42.320
Her face was small, white and thin, also much freckled.

04:42.320 --> 04:48.300
Her mouth was large, and so were her eyes, which looked green in some lights and moods, and gray in others.

04:49.120 --> 04:50.780
So far the ordinary observer.

04:51.420 --> 04:55.920
An extraordinary observer might have seen that the chin was very pointed and pronounced,

04:56.100 --> 05:01.060
that the big eyes were full of spirit and vivacity, that the mouth was sweet-lipped and expressive,

05:01.400 --> 05:03.000
that the forehead was broad and full.

05:03.400 --> 05:11.360
In short, our discerning extraordinary observer might have concluded that no commonplace soul inhabited the body of that stray woman child

05:11.360 --> 05:14.880
of whom shy Matthew Cuthbert was so ludicrously afraid.

05:15.840 --> 05:18.820
Matthew, however, was spared the ordeal of speaking first.

05:19.440 --> 05:22.860
For as soon as she concluded that he was coming to her, she stood up,

05:23.120 --> 05:27.620
grasping with one thin, brown hand the handle of a shabby, old-fashioned carpet-bag.

05:28.040 --> 05:29.560
The other she held out to him.

05:30.520 --> 05:36.220
I suppose you are Mr. Matthew Cuthbert of Green Gables, she said in a particularly sweet, clear voice.

05:36.460 --> 05:38.100
I am very glad to see you.

05:38.100 --> 05:44.220
I was beginning to be afraid you weren't coming for me, and I was imagining all the things that might have happened to prevent you.

05:44.480 --> 05:46.960
I had made up my mind that if you didn't come for me tonight,

05:47.260 --> 05:52.460
I'd go down the track to that big wild cherry tree at the bend and climb up into it to stay all night.

05:53.120 --> 05:54.540
I wouldn't be a bit afraid.

05:54.840 --> 06:00.120
It would be lovely to sleep in a wild cherry tree all white with bloom in the moonshine, don't you think?

06:00.440 --> 06:03.760
You could imagine you were dwelling in marble halls, couldn't you?

06:03.980 --> 06:07.500
And I was quite sure you would come for me in the morning if you didn't come tonight.

06:08.620 --> 06:14.460
Matthew had taken the scrawny little and awkwardly in his, and then and there he decided what to do.

06:15.020 --> 06:18.740
He could not tell this child with the glowing eyes that there had been a mistake.

06:19.240 --> 06:21.440
He would take her home and let Marilla do that.

06:22.040 --> 06:26.100
She couldn't be left at Bright River anyhow, no matter what mistake had been made.

06:26.720 --> 06:31.560
So all questions and explanations might as well be deferred until he was safely back at Green Gables.

06:32.800 --> 06:35.540
I'm sorry I was late, he said shyly.

06:35.540 --> 06:38.220
Come along, the horse is over in the yard.

06:38.580 --> 06:39.360
Give me your bag.

06:40.660 --> 06:43.380
Oh, I can carry it, the child responded cheerfully.

06:43.740 --> 06:44.500
It isn't heavy.

06:44.860 --> 06:48.180
I've got all my worldly belongings in it, but it isn't heavy.

06:48.880 --> 06:51.920
And if it isn't carried in just a certain way, the handle pulls out.

06:52.280 --> 06:55.220
So I'd better keep it, because I know the exact knack of it.

06:55.480 --> 06:57.040
It's an extremely old carpet bag.

06:58.400 --> 07:03.080
Oh, I'm very glad you've come, even if it would have been nice to sleep in a wild cherry tree.

07:03.080 --> 07:05.880
We've got to drive a long piece, haven't we?

07:06.120 --> 07:07.860
Mrs. Spencer said it was eight miles.

07:08.300 --> 07:10.160
I'm glad, because I love driving.

07:10.860 --> 07:14.500
Oh, it seems so wonderful that I'm going to live with you and belong to you.

07:14.780 --> 07:17.360
I've never belonged to anybody, not really.

07:17.940 --> 07:19.740
But the asylum was the worst.

07:20.240 --> 07:23.080
I've only been in it four months, but that was enough.

07:23.680 --> 07:28.680
I don't suppose you ever were an orphan in an asylum, so you can't possibly understand what it is like.

07:29.060 --> 07:31.020
It's worse than anything you could imagine.

07:31.020 --> 07:35.900
Mrs. Spencer said it was wicked of me to talk like that, but I didn't mean to be wicked.

07:36.540 --> 07:39.580
It's so easy to be wicked without knowing it, isn't it?

07:40.500 --> 07:42.780
They were good, you know, the asylum people.

07:43.120 --> 07:48.020
But there is so little scope for the imagination in an asylum, only just in the other orphans.

07:48.560 --> 07:50.960
It was pretty interesting to imagine things about them.

07:51.200 --> 07:55.680
To imagine that perhaps the girl who sat next to you was really the daughter of a belted earl

07:55.680 --> 08:01.720
who had been stolen away from her parents in her infancy by a cruel nurse who died before she could confess.

08:02.380 --> 08:07.920
I used to lie awake at nights and imagine things like that, because I didn't have the time in the day.

08:08.380 --> 08:09.960
I guess that's why I'm so thin.

08:10.360 --> 08:12.680
I am dreadfully thin, ain't I?

08:12.920 --> 08:14.600
There isn't a pick on my bones.

08:15.140 --> 08:18.580
I do love to imagine I'm nice and plump with dimples on my elbows.

08:19.680 --> 08:24.120
With this, Matthew's companion stopped talking, partly because she was out of breath

08:24.120 --> 08:26.640
and partly because they had reached the buggy.

08:26.840 --> 08:31.500
Not another word did she say until they had left the village and were driving down a steep little hill,

08:31.720 --> 08:35.080
the road part of which had been cut so deeply into the soft soil

08:35.080 --> 08:39.720
that the banks fringed with blooming wild cherry trees and slim white birches

08:39.720 --> 08:41.340
were several feet above their heads.

08:42.540 --> 08:47.280
The child put out her hand and broke off a branch of wild plum that brushed against the side of the buggy.

08:47.820 --> 08:49.120
Isn't that beautiful?

08:49.500 --> 08:53.160
What did that tree leaning out from the bank all white and lacy make you think of?

08:53.160 --> 08:53.960
She asked.

08:54.800 --> 08:57.940
Well, now, I don't know, said Matthew.

08:59.360 --> 09:03.900
Why, a bride, of course, a bride all in white with a lovely misty veil.

09:04.320 --> 09:07.460
I've never seen one, but I can imagine what she would look like.

09:07.920 --> 09:09.960
I don't ever expect to be a bride myself.

09:10.360 --> 09:14.960
I'm so homely nobody will ever want to marry me, unless it might be a foreign missionary.

09:15.500 --> 09:18.140
I suppose a foreign missionary mightn't be very particular.

09:18.940 --> 09:21.600
But I do hope that some day I shall have a white dress.

09:21.600 --> 09:24.240
That is my highest ideal of earthly bliss.

09:24.740 --> 09:26.100
I just love pretty clothes.

09:26.580 --> 09:29.320
And I've never had a pretty dress in my life that I can remember.

09:30.040 --> 09:32.740
But, of course, it's all the more to look forward to, isn't it?

09:32.920 --> 09:35.120
And then I can imagine that I'm dressed gorgeously.

09:36.280 --> 09:38.780
This morning when I left the asylum I felt so ashamed

09:38.780 --> 09:41.420
because I had to wear this horrible old wincey dress.

09:41.960 --> 09:43.860
All the orphans had to wear them, you know.

09:44.240 --> 09:48.320
A merchant at Hopeton last winter donated 300 yards of wincey to the asylum.

09:48.880 --> 09:51.280
Some people said it was because he couldn't sell it.

09:51.280 --> 09:55.160
But I'd rather believe that it was out of the kindness of his heart, wouldn't you?

09:55.700 --> 10:00.100
When we got on the train I felt as if everybody must be looking at me and pitying me.

10:00.520 --> 10:04.860
But I just went to work and imagined that I had on the most beautiful pale blue silk dress.

10:05.240 --> 10:09.000
Because when you are imagining, you might as well imagine something worthwhile

10:09.000 --> 10:11.740
and a big hat, all flowers and knotting plumes,

10:12.240 --> 10:14.740
and a gold watch, and kid gloves and boots.

10:15.400 --> 10:17.040
I felt cheered up right away

10:17.040 --> 10:20.060
and I enjoyed my trip to the island with all my might.

10:21.180 --> 10:23.700
I wasn't a bit sick coming over in the boat.

10:24.240 --> 10:27.120
Neither was Mrs. Spencer, although she generally is.

10:27.760 --> 10:31.620
She said she hadn't time to get sick watching to see that I didn't fall overboard.

10:32.640 --> 10:35.160
She said she never saw the bead of me for prowling about.

10:35.740 --> 10:39.960
But if it kept her from being seasick, it's a mercy I did prowl, isn't it?

10:40.300 --> 10:43.320
And I wanted to see everything that was to be seen on that boat

10:43.320 --> 10:45.960
because I didn't know whether I'd ever have another opportunity.

10:46.600 --> 10:50.180
Oh, there are a lot more cherry trees all in bloom.

10:50.680 --> 10:52.720
This island is the bloomiest place.

10:53.260 --> 10:56.740
I just love it already and I'm so glad I'm going to live here.

10:57.280 --> 11:00.900
I've always heard that Prince Edward Island was the prettiest place in the world

11:00.900 --> 11:05.520
and I used to imagine I was living here, but I never really expected I would.

11:06.180 --> 11:09.540
It's delightful when your imaginations come true, isn't it?

11:10.060 --> 11:11.880
But those red roads are so funny.

11:11.880 --> 11:16.360
When we got into the train at Charlottetown and the red roads began to flash past,

11:16.780 --> 11:20.720
I asked Mrs. Spencer what made them red and she said she didn't know

11:20.720 --> 11:23.440
and for pity's sake not to ask her any more questions.

11:24.340 --> 11:26.800
She said I must have asked her a thousand already.

11:27.640 --> 11:29.200
I suppose I had, too.

11:29.540 --> 11:32.540
But how are you going to find out about things if you don't ask questions?

11:33.360 --> 11:35.180
And what does make the roads red?

11:36.300 --> 11:39.540
Well, now, I don't know, said Matthew.

11:40.300 --> 11:42.960
Well, that is one of the things to find out sometime.

11:43.800 --> 11:46.860
Isn't it splendid to think of all the things there are to find out about?

11:47.200 --> 11:49.240
It just makes me feel glad to be alive.

11:49.820 --> 11:51.440
It's such an interesting world.

11:52.060 --> 11:55.500
It wouldn't be half so interesting if we knew all about everything, would it?

11:55.900 --> 11:58.240
There would be no scope for imagination then, would there?

11:59.200 --> 12:00.720
But am I talking too much?

12:01.080 --> 12:02.920
People are always telling me I do.

12:03.600 --> 12:05.020
Would you rather I didn't talk?

12:05.340 --> 12:06.840
If you say so, I'll stop.

12:06.840 --> 12:11.800
I can stop when I make up my mind to, although it's difficult.

12:13.080 --> 12:15.920
Matthew, much to his own surprise, was enjoying himself.

12:16.120 --> 12:20.900
Like most quiet folks, he liked talkative people when they were willing to do the talking themselves

12:20.900 --> 12:23.100
and did not expect him to keep up his end of it.

12:23.620 --> 12:26.680
But he had never expected to enjoy the society of a little girl.

12:27.380 --> 12:31.160
Women were bad enough in all conscience, but little girls were worse.

12:31.740 --> 12:36.360
He detested the way they had of sidling past him timidly with sideways glances

12:36.360 --> 12:40.880
as if they expected him to gobble them up at a mouthful if they ventured to say a word.

12:41.640 --> 12:44.380
That was the avidly type of well-bred little girls.

12:45.540 --> 12:49.840
But this freckled witch was very different, and although he found it rather difficult

12:49.840 --> 12:53.120
for his slower intelligence to keep up with her brisk mental processes,

12:53.700 --> 12:55.760
he thought that he kind of liked her chatter.

12:56.540 --> 12:58.300
So he said as shyly as usual,

12:59.320 --> 13:02.340
Oh, you can talk as much as you like. I don't mind.

13:03.360 --> 13:07.740
Oh, I'm so glad. I know you and I are going to get along together fine.

13:08.280 --> 13:10.700
It's such a relief to talk when one wants to,

13:10.760 --> 13:13.220
and not to be told that children should be seen and not heard.

13:13.780 --> 13:16.700
I've had that said to me a million times if I had once.

13:17.360 --> 13:19.720
And people laugh at me because I use big words.

13:20.260 --> 13:24.560
But if you have big ideas, you have to use big words to express them, haven't you?

13:25.420 --> 13:28.700
Well, now, that seems reasonable, said Matthew.

13:29.640 --> 13:32.380
Mrs. Spencer said that my tongue must be hung in the middle.

13:32.900 --> 13:35.900
But it isn't. It's firmly fastened at one end.

13:36.760 --> 13:39.320
Mrs. Spencer said your place was named Green Gables.

13:39.820 --> 13:44.000
I asked her all about it, and she said there were trees all around it.

13:44.140 --> 13:46.840
I was gladder than ever. I just love trees.

13:47.780 --> 13:49.680
And there weren't any at all about the asylum.

13:49.920 --> 13:52.960
Only a few poor weeny-teeny things out in front,

13:53.040 --> 13:55.160
with little white-washed cagey things about them.

13:55.160 --> 13:58.300
They just looked like orphans themselves, those trees did.

13:58.860 --> 14:01.160
It used to make me want to cry to look at them.

14:01.600 --> 14:02.700
I used to say to them,

14:03.160 --> 14:04.900
Oh, you poor little things!

14:05.420 --> 14:09.000
If you were out in a great big woods with other trees all about you,

14:09.120 --> 14:11.900
and little mosses and June bells growing over your roots,

14:12.060 --> 14:15.480
and a brook not far away, and birds singing in the branches,

14:15.840 --> 14:17.380
you could grow, couldn't you?

14:18.000 --> 14:19.640
But you can't where you are.

14:20.340 --> 14:22.480
I know just how you feel, little trees.

14:22.480 --> 14:25.780
I felt sorry to leave them behind this morning.

14:26.060 --> 14:29.340
You do get so attached to things like that, don't you?

14:30.580 --> 14:32.680
Is there a brook anywhere near Green Gables?

14:33.040 --> 14:35.020
I forgot to ask Mrs. Spencer that.

14:36.360 --> 14:39.940
Well, now, yes, there's one right below the house.

14:41.200 --> 14:44.800
Fancy! It's always been one of my dreams to live near a brook.

14:45.260 --> 14:47.200
I never expected I would, though.

14:48.000 --> 14:50.000
Dreams don't often come true, do they?

14:50.000 --> 14:52.120
Wouldn't it be nice if they did?

14:53.020 --> 14:55.980
But just now I feel pretty nearly perfectly happy.

14:56.460 --> 15:00.140
I can't feel exactly perfectly happy, because, well,

15:00.560 --> 15:02.140
what color would you call this?

15:02.860 --> 15:06.180
She twitched one of her long glossy braids over her thin shoulder

15:06.180 --> 15:08.200
and held it up before Matthew's eyes.

15:09.220 --> 15:12.260
Matthew was not used to deciding on the tints of ladies' tresses,

15:12.300 --> 15:15.000
but in this case there couldn't be much doubt.

15:15.740 --> 15:17.880
It's red, ain't it? he said.

15:18.780 --> 15:21.260
The girl let the braid drop with a sigh

15:21.260 --> 15:23.260
that seemed to come from her very toes

15:23.260 --> 15:26.180
and exhale forth all the sorrows of the ages.

15:27.720 --> 15:30.440
Yes, it's red, she said resignedly.

15:31.240 --> 15:33.840
Now you see why I can't be perfectly happy.

15:34.540 --> 15:36.340
Nobody could who has red hair.

15:37.520 --> 15:39.460
I don't mind the other things so much,

15:39.540 --> 15:42.160
the freckles and the green eyes and my skinniness.

15:42.520 --> 15:44.100
I can imagine them away.

15:44.100 --> 15:48.460
I can imagine that I have a beautiful rose leaf complexion

15:48.460 --> 15:51.000
and lovely starry violet eyes,

15:51.740 --> 15:54.180
but I cannot imagine that red hair away.

15:54.840 --> 15:56.000
I do my best.

15:56.720 --> 16:00.420
I think to myself, now my hair is a glorious black,

16:01.080 --> 16:02.720
black as the raven's wing,

16:03.100 --> 16:06.020
but all the time I know it is just plain red,

16:06.480 --> 16:08.080
and it breaks my heart.

16:08.600 --> 16:10.540
It will be my lifelong sorrow.

16:10.540 --> 16:14.320
I read of a girl once in a novel who had a lifelong sorrow,

16:14.600 --> 16:16.020
but it wasn't red hair.

16:16.800 --> 16:20.360
Her hair was pure gold rippling back from her alabaster brow.

16:21.160 --> 16:23.980
What is an alabaster brow? I never could find out.

16:24.180 --> 16:25.180
Can you tell me?

16:26.300 --> 16:29.560
Well, no, I'm afraid I can't, said Matthew,

16:29.880 --> 16:31.260
who was getting a little dizzy.

16:32.080 --> 16:34.900
He felt as he had once felt in his rash youth

16:34.900 --> 16:37.980
when another boy had enticed him on the merry-go-round at a picnic.

16:38.640 --> 16:41.900
Well, whatever it was, it must have been something nice

16:41.900 --> 16:43.800
because she was divinely beautiful.

16:44.460 --> 16:47.560
Have you ever imagined what it must feel like to be divinely beautiful?

16:49.000 --> 16:53.700
Well, now, no, I haven't, confessed Matthew ingenuously.

16:54.820 --> 16:55.860
I have often.

16:56.580 --> 16:58.640
Which would you rather be if you had the choice,

16:59.200 --> 17:03.280
divinely beautiful or dazzlingly clever or angelically good?

17:04.300 --> 17:08.620
Well, now, I don't know exactly.

17:09.960 --> 17:10.780
Neither do I.

17:11.000 --> 17:12.320
I can never decide.

17:12.820 --> 17:14.440
But it doesn't make much real difference,

17:14.480 --> 17:16.600
for it isn't likely I'll ever be either.

17:17.460 --> 17:19.800
It's certain I'll never be angelically good.

17:20.400 --> 17:21.500
Mrs. Spencer says,

17:22.580 --> 17:28.740
Oh, Mr. Cuthbert! Oh, Mr. Cuthbert! Oh, Mr. Cuthbert!

17:29.540 --> 17:32.140
That was not what Mrs. Spencer had said.

17:32.140 --> 17:34.380
Neither had the child tumbled out of the buggy,

17:34.700 --> 17:36.640
nor had Matthew done anything astonishing.

17:37.580 --> 17:42.040
They had simply rounded a curve in the road and found themselves in the Avenue.

17:43.280 --> 17:45.480
The Avenue, so called by the Newbridge people,

17:45.660 --> 17:48.240
was a stretch of road four or five hundred yards long,

17:48.660 --> 17:51.600
completely arched over with huge, wide-spreading apple trees,

17:52.000 --> 17:54.280
planted years ago by an eccentric old farmer.

17:55.400 --> 17:58.400
Overhead was one long canopy of snowy, fragrant bloom.

17:58.960 --> 18:02.260
Below the boughs the air was full of a purple twilight,

18:03.020 --> 18:05.840
and far ahead a glimpse of painted sunset sky

18:05.840 --> 18:09.860
shone like a great rose window at the end of a cathedral aisle.

18:10.840 --> 18:12.800
Its beauty seemed to strike the child dumb.

18:13.420 --> 18:17.380
She leaned back in the buggy, her thin hands clasped before her,

18:17.540 --> 18:20.380
her face lifted rapturously to the white splendor above.

18:21.240 --> 18:24.740
Even when they had passed out and were driving down the long slope to Newbridge,

18:25.300 --> 18:26.600
she never moved or spoke.

18:27.600 --> 18:31.440
Still, with rapt face, she gazed afar into the sunset west,

18:31.660 --> 18:35.700
with eyes that saw visions trooping splendidly across the glowing background.

18:36.820 --> 18:40.180
Through Newbridge, a bustling little village where dogs barked at them

18:40.180 --> 18:43.420
and small boys hooted and curious faces peered from the windows,

18:43.700 --> 18:45.440
they drove, still in silence.

18:46.160 --> 18:49.960
When three more miles had dropped away behind them, the child had not spoken.

18:50.700 --> 18:54.700
She could keep silence, it was evident, as energetically she could talk.

18:55.980 --> 19:00.780
I guess you're feeling pretty tired and hungry, Matthew ventured to say at last,

19:01.080 --> 19:05.140
accounting for her long visitation of dumbness with the only reason he could think of.

19:05.580 --> 19:09.040
But we haven't very far to go now, only another mile.

19:10.120 --> 19:12.420
She came out of her reverie with a deep sigh,

19:12.600 --> 19:17.500
and looked at him with the dreamy gaze of a soul that had been wandering afar star-led.

19:18.320 --> 19:24.120
Oh, Mr. Cuthbert, she whispered, that place we came through, that white place,

19:24.120 --> 19:25.880
what was it?

19:26.760 --> 19:32.140
Well now, you mean the avenue, said Matthew after a few moments' profound reflection.

19:32.660 --> 19:34.360
It is a kind of pretty place.

19:35.620 --> 19:41.540
Pretty? Oh, pretty doesn't seem the right word to use, nor beautiful either.

19:41.960 --> 19:43.500
They don't go far enough.

19:44.420 --> 19:45.960
Oh, it was wonderful.

19:46.560 --> 19:50.480
It's the first thing I ever saw that couldn't be improved upon by my imagination.

19:51.220 --> 19:53.120
It just satisfies me here.

19:53.120 --> 19:55.140
She put one hand on her breast.

19:55.560 --> 19:58.700
It made a queer funny ache, and yet it was a pleasant ache.

19:59.400 --> 20:01.720
Did you ever have an ache like that, Mr. Cuthbert?

20:02.880 --> 20:06.460
Well now, I just can't recollect that I ever had.

20:07.640 --> 20:11.660
I have it lots of times, whenever I see anything royally beautiful.

20:12.580 --> 20:14.800
But they shouldn't call that lovely place the avenue.

20:15.260 --> 20:17.240
There is no meaning in a name like that.

20:18.000 --> 20:20.860
They should call it, let me see,

20:20.860 --> 20:22.960
the White Way of Delight.

20:23.460 --> 20:25.420
Isn't that a nice imaginative name?

20:26.320 --> 20:30.320
When I don't like the name of a place or a person, I always imagine a new one,

20:30.580 --> 20:32.060
and always think of them so.

20:32.820 --> 20:35.920
There was a girl at the asylum whose name was Hepzibah Jenkins,

20:36.560 --> 20:39.120
but I always imagined her as Rosalia Devere.

20:40.340 --> 20:46.040
Other people may call that place the avenue, but I shall always call it the White Way of Delight.

20:46.880 --> 20:50.260
Have we really only another mile to go before we get home?

20:51.100 --> 20:52.800
I'm glad and I'm sorry.

20:53.420 --> 20:55.820
I'm sorry because this drive has been so pleasant,

20:56.220 --> 20:58.620
and I'm always sorry when pleasant things end.

20:59.180 --> 21:03.100
Something still pleasanter may come after, but you can never be sure,

21:03.600 --> 21:05.860
and it's so often the case that it isn't pleasanter.

21:06.260 --> 21:08.180
That has been my experience anyhow.

21:08.900 --> 21:10.800
But I'm glad to think of getting home.

21:11.300 --> 21:14.280
You see, I've never had a real home since I can remember.

21:14.280 --> 21:20.560
It gives me that pleasant ache again just to think of coming to a really truly home.

21:21.720 --> 21:23.400
Oh, isn't that pretty?

21:24.420 --> 21:26.100
They had driven over the crest of a hill.

21:26.400 --> 21:31.060
Below them was a pond looking almost like a river, so long and winding was it.

21:31.860 --> 21:35.640
A bridge spanned it midway, and from there to its lower end,

21:35.800 --> 21:40.540
where an amber-hued belt of sand hills shut it in from the dark blue gulf beyond,

21:41.040 --> 21:43.460
the water was a glory of many shifting hues.

21:43.460 --> 21:47.980
The most spiritual shadings of crocus and rose and ethereal green,

21:48.540 --> 21:52.020
with other elusive tintings for which no name has ever been found.

21:52.780 --> 21:56.700
Above the bridge, the pond ran up into fringing groves of fir and maple,

21:57.200 --> 22:00.100
and lay all darkly translucent in their wavering shadows.

22:00.760 --> 22:06.380
Here and there a wild plum leaned out from the bank like a white-clad girl tiptoeing to her own reflection.

22:07.340 --> 22:11.660
From the marsh at the head of the pond came the clear mournfully sweet chorus of the frogs.

22:11.660 --> 22:16.760
There was a little gray house peering around a white apple orchard on a slope beyond,

22:17.140 --> 22:21.840
and although it was not yet quite dark, a light was shining from one of its windows.

22:22.960 --> 22:25.400
That's Barry's pond, said Matthew.

22:26.620 --> 22:28.540
Oh, I don't like that name either.

22:29.180 --> 22:34.520
I shall call it, let me see, the Lake of Shining Waters.

22:35.420 --> 22:37.620
Yes, that is the right name for it.

22:38.120 --> 22:39.700
I know because of the thrill.

22:39.700 --> 22:43.460
When I hit on a name that suits exactly, it gives me a thrill.

22:44.620 --> 22:46.020
Do things ever give you a thrill?

22:47.220 --> 22:48.180
Matthew ruminated.

22:49.340 --> 22:50.520
Well, now, yes.

22:51.080 --> 22:56.440
It always kind of gives me a thrill to see them ugly white grubs that spade up in the cucumber beds.

22:57.200 --> 22:58.560
I hate the look of them.

22:59.920 --> 23:03.420
Oh, I don't think that can be exactly the same kind of a thrill.

23:04.000 --> 23:05.000
Do you think it can?

23:05.520 --> 23:10.040
There doesn't seem to be much connection between grubs and Lakes of Shining Waters, does there?

23:10.940 --> 23:12.880
But why do other people call it Barry's pond?

23:14.000 --> 23:17.300
I reckon because Mr. Barry lives up there in that house.

23:17.880 --> 23:19.700
Orchard Slope's the name of his place.

23:20.440 --> 23:23.940
If it wasn't for that big bush behind it, you could see Green Gables from here.

23:24.240 --> 23:28.880
But we have to go over the bridge and round by the road, so it's near half a mile further.

23:30.100 --> 23:32.600
Has Mr. Barry any little girls?

23:32.600 --> 23:34.840
Well, not so very little either.

23:34.940 --> 23:36.200
About my size.

23:37.740 --> 23:39.260
He's got one about eleven.

23:39.580 --> 23:40.660
Her name is Diana.

23:42.080 --> 23:44.840
Oh, with a long in-drawing of breath.

23:45.500 --> 23:47.920
What a perfectly lovely name.

23:49.420 --> 23:51.340
Well, now, I don't know.

23:51.800 --> 23:55.140
There's something dreadfully heathen-ish about it, seems to me.

23:55.500 --> 23:59.680
I'd rather Jane or Mary, or some sensible name like that.

23:59.680 --> 24:06.980
But when Diana was born, there was a schoolmaster boarding there, and they gave him the naming of her, and he called her Diana.

24:08.120 --> 24:11.800
I wish there had been a schoolmaster like that around when I was born, then.

24:12.760 --> 24:14.120
Oh, here we are at the bridge.

24:14.780 --> 24:16.400
I'm going to shut my eyes tight.

24:16.620 --> 24:18.460
I'm always afraid going over bridges.

24:19.020 --> 24:24.940
I can't help imagining that perhaps just as we get to the middle, they'll crumple up like a jackknife and nip us.

24:25.200 --> 24:26.560
So I shut my eyes.

24:26.560 --> 24:30.740
But I always have to open them for all when I think we're getting near the middle.

24:31.440 --> 24:35.540
Because, you see, if the bridge did crumple up, I'd want to see it crumple.

24:35.960 --> 24:37.580
What a jolly rumble it makes.

24:38.100 --> 24:39.820
I always like the rumble part of it.

24:40.080 --> 24:40.880
Isn't it splendid?

24:41.000 --> 24:43.020
There are so many things to like in this world.

24:43.900 --> 24:44.740
There, we're over.

24:44.900 --> 24:46.100
Now I'll look back.

24:46.880 --> 24:48.800
Good night, dear lake of shining waters.

24:49.420 --> 24:53.400
I always say good night to the things I love, just as I would to people.

24:53.580 --> 24:54.840
I think they like it.

24:55.380 --> 24:58.040
That water looks as if it was smiling at me.

24:59.360 --> 25:02.820
When they had driven up the further hill and around a corner, Matthew said,

25:03.360 --> 25:04.900
We're pretty near home now.

25:05.260 --> 25:06.580
There's Green Gables over.

25:07.000 --> 25:14.180
Oh, don't tell me, she interrupted breathlessly, catching at his partially raised arm and shutting her eyes that she might not see the gesture.

25:14.700 --> 25:15.400
Let me guess.

25:15.740 --> 25:17.100
I'm sure I'll guess right.

25:17.820 --> 25:20.000
She opened her eyes and looked about her.

25:20.340 --> 25:21.820
They were on the crust of a hill.

25:21.820 --> 25:27.120
The sun had set some time since, but the landscape was still clear in the mellow afterlight.

25:27.880 --> 25:31.840
In the west, a dark church spire rose up against a marigold sky.

25:32.560 --> 25:38.880
Below was a little valley, and beyond a long, gently rising slope with snug farmsteads scattered along it.

25:39.380 --> 25:42.420
From one to another, the child's eyes darted eager and wistful.

25:42.800 --> 25:50.920
At last, they lingered on one away to the left, far back from the road, dimly white with blossoming trees in the twilight of the surrounding woods.

25:51.540 --> 25:58.700
Over it, in the stainless southwest sky, a great crystal-white star was shining like a glamp of guidance and promise.

25:59.940 --> 26:02.000
That's it, isn't it? she said, pointing.

26:03.060 --> 26:05.700
Matthew slapped the rains and the sorrows back delightedly.

26:06.660 --> 26:11.420
Well, now you've guessed it, but I reckon Mrs. Spencer described it so as you could tell.

26:12.380 --> 26:17.740
No, she didn't. Really, she didn't. All she said might just as well have been about most of those other places.

26:17.740 --> 26:24.020
I hadn't any real idea what it looked like, but just as soon as I saw it, I felt it was home.

26:24.740 --> 26:27.140
Oh, it seems as if I must be in a dream.

26:27.900 --> 26:34.200
Do you know, my arm must be black and blue from the elbow up, for I've pinched myself so many times today.

26:35.160 --> 26:40.860
Every little while a horrible sickening feeling would come over me, and I'd be so afraid it was all a dream.

26:41.440 --> 26:43.660
Then I'd pinch myself to see if it was real.

26:43.660 --> 26:52.700
Until suddenly I remembered that even supposing it was only a dream, I'd better go on dreaming as long as I could, so I stopped pinching.

26:53.120 --> 26:55.740
But it is real, and we're nearly home.

26:56.860 --> 26:59.540
With a sigh of rapture she relapsed into silence.

27:00.620 --> 27:01.840
Matthew stirred uneasily.

27:02.280 --> 27:10.340
He felt glad that it would be Marilla and not he who would have to tell this waif of the world that the home she longed for was not to be hers after all.

27:10.340 --> 27:21.840
They drove over Lynn's Hollow where it was already quite dark, but not so dark that Mrs. Rachel could not see them from her window vantage, and up the hill and into the long lane of green gables.

27:23.160 --> 27:29.200
By the time they arrived at the house, Matthew was shrinking from the approaching revelation with an energy he did not understand.

27:29.800 --> 27:36.540
It was not of Marilla or himself he was thinking of the trouble this mistake was probably going to make for them, but of the child's disappointment.

27:36.540 --> 27:51.040
When he thought of that rapt light being quenched in her eyes, he had an uncomfortable feeling that he was going to assist at murdering something, much the same feeling that came over him when he had to kill a lamb or calf or any other innocent little creature.

27:52.620 --> 27:58.140
The yard was quite dark as they turned into it, and the poplar leaves were rustling silkily all round it.

27:58.980 --> 28:05.820
Listen to the trees talking in their sleep, she whispered, as he lifted her to the ground. What nice dreams they must have!

28:06.880 --> 28:12.860
Then, holding tightly to the carpet bag, which contained all her worldly goods, she followed him into the house.

